If geographically unique analysts deliver forecasts that contain distinct information on average, we would expect the market to react more strongly to forecast revisions made by unique analysts relative to analysts who are in an area with multiple analysts covering the same firm. Van Nieuwerburgh and Veldkamp (2009) argue that when fewer agents share an advantage in the same local risk, locals have a larger advantage relative to the average. We test this idea using the following model: $$\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
\textit{CAR}_{j,t} = &\beta_1 \textit{Unique}\ \textit{Analyst}_{i,j,q} + \beta_2
\textit{Revision}_{i,j,t} + \beta_3 \textit{Unique}\ \textit{Analyst}_{i,j,t}\\
&\times \textit{Revision}_{i,j,t}
+ \sum\limits_{k}\beta_k \textit{Controls}_{i,j,t} + \Gamma \textit{FE} + \epsilon_{i,j,t}
\end{split}
\end{equation}$$ (8) |${\it CAR}_{j,t}$| is the market-adjusted stock return for firm |$j$| during the 3-day window surrounding an analyst revision on day |$t$|⁠ , |${\it Unique\ Analyst}_{i,j,t}$| is a dummy that takes the value of one when an analyst |$i$| is the only one covering firm |$j$| from their MSA, and |${\it Revision}_{i,j,t}$| is either the change in the analyst’s EPS forecast (scaled by the stock price as of the end of the prior fiscal year) or the change in Buy/Sell/Hold recommendation. For the forecast revision tests, we require an analyst to revise a forecast within a quarter. We control for firm size, book-to-market, turnover, forecast age, the logarithm of analyst total and firm-specific experience, the logarithm of the number of stocks the analyst covers, an indicator if the analyst is located in the same MSA as the firm’s headquarters, and an indicator if an analyst is an all-star. We include |${\it Firm}\times {\it YQ}$| and |${\it Analyst}$| fixed effects. We also require that at least two analysts cover the firm. The variable of interest is the interaction term |${\it Unique\ analyst}_{i,j,t}\times {\it Revision}_{i,j,t}$|⁠ , which will estimate the marginal market reaction to geographically unique analyst revisions.

Table 9presents results for the market’s reaction to geographically unique analysts. Consistent with prior literature (e.g.,Green et al. 2014;Hirshleifer et al. 2019;Chen, Mayew, and Yan 2021), the main effect on both forecast and recommendation revisions is positive and statistically significant, suggesting price-relevant information is embedded in revisions. We find the market reacts relatively more to geographically unique analysts, as the coefficient for the interaction term is also positive and significant. Specifically, the abnormal stock reaction is 9.4|$\%$|–13.2|$\%$|stronger when a unique analyst makes a revision relative to when an analyst in a common MSA makes a revision. The effect is consistent when looking at both earnings and recommendation revisions. The consistency of the results after including|${\it Analyst}$|fixed effects is particularly compelling as it suggests the market recognizes when the same analyst revises a forecast for a firm for which they are a unique analyst relative to when that analyst revises for another firm where they are a geographically common analyst. These findings are consistent with our prior results, suggesting that geographic information is an important component of analyst forecasts.

