Our final tests analyze whether the information content in stock prices is affected by analyst geographic dispersion. Because our prior results provide evidence that analysts incorporate local firm information into forecasts, a natural implication would be this firm-specific geographic information is incorporated into prices. Further, the model of Goldstein and Yang (2015) proposes that a firm’s stock price will be more informative about future cash flows when the information that investors can access is more diverse. Given the importance of analysts as information providers, we propose that the prices of stocks with more geographically diverse analysts will be more informative about future earnings. To empirically test the prediction of Goldstein and Yang (2015) , we follow the prior literature (e.g., Kothari and Sloan 1992 ; Israeli, Lee, and Sridharan 2017 ; Zhu 2019 ) and use the following future earnings response coefficient model: $$\begin{align}
\textit{Ret}_{j,t} & = \beta_1 *\textit{Earn}_{j,t-1} + \beta_2*\textit{Earn}_{j,t} + \beta_3*\textit{Earn}_{j,t+1} + \beta_4*\textit{Disperse}_{j,t} \nonumber \\
&\quad{} +\beta_5*\textit{Disperse}_{j,t}\times \textit{Earn}_{j,t-1} + \beta_6*\textit{Disperse}_{j,t} \times \textit{Earn}_{j,t} \\
&\quad{} +\beta_7*\textit{Disperse}_{j,t} \times \textit{Earn}_{j,t+1} + \sum\limits_{k}\beta_k*\textit{Controls}_{j,t} + \Gamma*\textit{FE} + \epsilon_{j,t}.\nonumber
\end{align}$$ (9) |${\it Ret}_{j,t}$| is the annual market-adjusted return for firm |$j$| during fiscal year |$t$|⁠ , |${\it Earn}_{j,t}$| is the firm’s earnings before extraordinary items in year |$t$| scaled by market value at the end of the previous fiscal year, and |${\it Disperse}$| is an indicator that equals one if a firm’s analysts are above the median in terms of geographic dispersion as measured by either the number of unique MSAs or our analyst dispersion measure. The variable of interest is |${\it Disperse}_{j,t} \times {\it Earn}_{j,t+1}$|⁠ , which will estimate the marginal price informativeness of firms with geographically dispersed analysts. We follow Israeli, Lee, and Sridharan (2017) and control for future returns, the logarithm of market cap, the number of analysts covering the firm, the logarithm of asset growth, ROA, and an indicator variable that equals one if the firm has negative earnings. We also control for the interaction of |${\it Disperse}_{j,t}$| with earnings for the current and prior year. We include |${\it Firm}$| and |${\it Year}$| fixed effects and cluster standard errors by firm.

Table 10reports results for estimating Equation (9). Consistent with prior literature, we find the coefficient for future earnings is positive and significant. We further find a positive and significant coefficient for the interaction of future earnings with our indicators for high analyst dispersion. The result is consistent using number of unique analyst MSAs or the MSA dispersion index to measure geographic coverage. Consistent with the prediction ofGoldstein and Yang (2015), stock prices of firms with more diverse information from geographically dispersed analysts are more predictive of future earnings.

